Here is the complete breakdown of how your wolof stranscriptionb could be better


1. Audio Capture (
hooks/useSpeech.ts
)
This hook manages the browser's microphone input using the MediaRecorder API.

Initialization: It checks for supported MIME types (like audio/webm or audio/mp4).
Recording: When startListening is called, it captures the microphone stream and stores data chunks.
Completion: When stopped, it combines chunks into a single Blob and triggers the onRecordingComplete callback.
typescript
// hooks/useSpeech.ts

// ... (setup logic)
mediaRecorder.onstop = () => {
    // Combines recorded chunks into a single audio file (Blob)
    const audioBlob = new Blob(audioChunksRef.current, { type: mimeType });
    // Sends the blob back to the main component
    onRecordingComplete(audioBlob, mimeType);
    stopAudioProcessing();
};
2. Processing & Sending (
App.tsx
)
The main application component receives the audio blob, converts it to a format Gemini can accept (Base64), and initiates the transcription.

typescript
// App.tsx

const handleRecordingComplete = async (audioBlob: Blob, mimeType: string) => {
    try {
        // 1. Convert the raw Audio Blob to a Base64 string
        const reader = new FileReader();
        reader.readAsDataURL(audioBlob);

        reader.onloadend = async () => {
            // Remove the data URL prefix (e.g., "data:audio/webm;base64,")
            const base64 = (reader.result as string).split(',')[1];

            // 2. Call the service to transcribe
            const text = await transcribeAudio(base64, mimeType);

            // 3. If text is found, send it as a user message
            if (text.trim()) {
                sendMessage(text);
            }
        };
    } catch (e) {
        console.error("Transcription failed", e);
    }
};
3. Transcription Service (
services/geminiService.ts
)
This is where the "magic" happens. Instead of sending the audio to Hugging Face, we send it directly to Gemini with a specific prompt instructing it to transcribe.

Model: Uses gemini-2.5-flash (MODELS.FAST), which is optimized for speed and multimodal tasks.
Prompt: Explicitly tells the AI to handle Wolof or French and return only the raw text.
typescript
// services/geminiService.ts

export async function transcribeAudio(audioBase64: string, mimeType: string): Promise<string> {
    const contents: Content[] = [{
        role: 'user',
        parts: [
            // The audio data is embedded directly in the request
            { inlineData: { data: audioBase64, mimeType } },

            // The prompt guides the model's behavior
            { text: `Transcris cet audio avec précision. Ignore les bruits de fond. Si c'est du Wolof, transcris-le en Wolof. Si c'est du Français, en Français. Renvoie uniquement le texte brut.` }
        ]
    }];

    // Sends to Gemini Flash
    return callGemini(MODELS.FAST, contents);
}
Summary
The "fluent Wolof understanding"  must comes from Gemini 1.5 Flash's vast training data, which includes low-resource languages like Wolof. By prompting it specifically to "Transcribe in Wolof if it is Wolof," we leverage its internal translation and phonetic understanding capabilities without needing a specialized external mode

